#X text 50 57 A crossover filter splits an audio in different frequency bands. It's used in audio for splitting and routing signals to different speakers (such as: woofer \, tweeter) \, so each gets a proper band of frequencies (low in woofer \, high in tweeter).;
#X text 298 268 Hz (cutoff);
#X text 371 317 Hz (cutoff);
#X text 50 139 Below we have a crossover setting by parallel lowpass and highpass filters with the same cutoff. We use [lop~] and [hip~] filters in cascade \, open the subpatches for more details., f 59;
#X obj 356 18 declare -path else;
#X obj 261 410 out~;
#X obj 75 362 out~;
#N canvas 125 85 436 329 highpass 0;
#X floatatom 144 101 5 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X obj 75 52 inlet~;
#X obj 119 253 outlet~;
#X obj 144 52 inlet;
#X text 178 140 4 [hip~] filters in cascade;
#X obj 75 137 hip~;
#X obj 88 163 hip~;
#X obj 103 189 hip~;
#X obj 119 215 hip~;
#X connect 0 0 5 1;
#X connect 0 0 6 1;
#X connect 0 0 7 1;
#X connect 0 0 8 1;
#X connect 1 0 5 0;
#X connect 3 0 0 0;
#X connect 5 0 6 0;
#X connect 6 0 7 0;
#X connect 7 0 8 0;
#X connect 8 0 2 0;
#X restore 162 311 pd highpass;
#X text 61 494 We also have the [crossover~] object from ELSE \, a ready made 4th order crossover filter. But this is a butterworth filter instead (we'll see more details on the butterworth filter topology later in this tutorial).;
